## Executive Summary
In this lab, I analyze the Stuxnet attack, widely regarded as the first cyberweapon 
ever deployed in warfare. Stuxnet is referred to as a virus, but in reality, it is a 
computer worm that is believed to have been active since at least 2005 and targeted 
the Natanz uranium enrichment facility. The worm exploited four zero-day
vulnerabilities of Windows systems, and its main goal was to damage equipment,
specifically the uranium enrichment centrifuges. Stuxnet remained undetectable for 
five years, masking its actions by sending falsified sensor readings, until it was
finally discovered in 2010 as the most sophisticated malware of its time. It is believed
that the worm was a joint operation of the United States and Israel called Operation Olympic
Games, although neither country has formally admitted responsibility.

---

## Technical Analysis
### The Vulnerability
Stuxnet was a sophisticated worm programmed that initially targeted Windows systems, by using
four zero-day vulnerabilities - previously unknown flaws for which no patch existed 
at the time of exploitation. The simultaneous use of four zero-day vulnerabilities points
to nation-state resources, as it required a lot of research investment.

The second phase of the worm's design was to target the Siemens Step7 software that was 
used to control the speed of uranium enrichment centrifuge motors. Once the worm identified
the Programmable Logic Controllers, it manipulated the centrifuge operating speeds beyond safe
parameters to sabotage the equipment, while masking its actions by falsifying the sensor readings.
The nuclear facility's network was considered air gapped, as it had no external communication with
other networks, so the attackers used infected USB drives to infect the network.

### How the Attack works
The first layer of the attack was to infect the air-gapped network of the
nuclear facility. This was done by someone who consciously or subconsciously added the
malware physically, through an infected USB drive. Once inside, it started spreading
across the Windows systems looking for its designated target.

The worm was searching to activate its payload on a very specific PLC configuration, 
remaining dormant on any other systems. Once it found the  Siemens Step7 software, 
the second layer started. Centrifuges spin at speeds of approximately 1,000 Hz, creating a force 
stronger than gravity to separate the uranium gas. The worm manipulated the centrifuge's operating
speed, causing enough stress to damage it. For the worm to stay undetected, it 
was waiting weeks to slow down the centrifuges after accelerating them temporarily, 
making its presence hard to detect.

### What an Attacker Gains
The worm is calculated to have destroyed approximately 1,000 centrifuges and reduced the 
operational capacity from 4,700 to 3,900, setting back the Iranian nuclear program by an 
estimated minimum of two years. Stuxnet changed the view of many nations regarding 
cyberweapons, as it proved the real-world physical destruction it can cause. Every 
nation-state cyber program that exists today was shaped by what Stuxnet demonstrated was 
possible.

---

##Impact Assessment
The destruction of centrifuges in the Natanz facility was an operationally paralyzing situation 
for the facility engineers, since they could not detect what was causing the damage. The world 
watching a nuclear facility on an air-gapped network getting destroyed by a worm from the inside
made governments and security agencies worldwide worry about the destruction it could cause 
on any other critical government infrastructure, as Stuxnet demonstrated how a cyberweapon 
can damage a nation's most secure systems and networks.

